44Ac 19:3 "Well, then, what kind of baptism did you receive?" Paul asked. "The baptism of John," they answered. 
44Ac 19:4 Paul said, "The baptism of John was for those who turned from their sins; and he told the people of Israel to believe in the one who was coming after him - that is, in Jesus." 
44Ac 19:5 When they heard this, they were baptized in the name of the Lord Jesus. 
44Ac 19:6 Paul placed his hands on them, and the Holy Spirit came upon them; they spoke in strange tongues and also proclaimed God's message. 
44Ac 19:7 They were about twelve men in all. 
44Ac 19:8 Paul went into the synagogue and for three months spoke boldly with the people, holding discussions with them and trying to convince them about the Kingdom of God. 
44Ac 19:9 But some of them were stubborn and would not believe, and before the whole group they said evil things about the Way of the Lord. So Paul left them and took the believers with him, and every day he held discussions in the lecture hall of Tyrannus. 
44Ac 19:10 This went on for two years, so that all the people who lived in the province of Asia, both Jews and Gentiles, heard the word of the Lord. 
44Ac 19:11 God was performing unusual miracles through Paul. 
44Ac 19:12 Even handkerchiefs and aprons he had used were taken to the sick, and their diseases were driven away, and the evil spirits would go out of them. 
44Ac 19:13 Some Jews who traveled around and drove out evil spirits also tried to use the name of the Lord Jesus to do this. They said to the evil spirits, "I command you in the name of Jesus, whom Paul preaches." 
44Ac 19:14 Seven brothers, who were the sons of a Jewish High Priest named Sceva, were doing this. 
44Ac 19:15 But the evil spirit said to them, "I know Jesus, and I know about Paul; but you - who are you?" 
44Ac 19:16 The man who had the evil spirit in him attacked them with such violence that he overpowered them all. They ran away from his house, wounded and with their clothes torn off. 
44Ac 19:17 All the Jews and Gentiles who lived in Ephesus heard about this; they were all filled with fear, and the name of the Lord Jesus was given greater honor. 
44Ac 19:18 Many of the believers came, publicly admitting and revealing what they had done. 
44Ac 19:19 Many of those who had practiced magic brought their books together and burned them in public. They added up the price of the books, and the total came to fifty thousand silver coins. 
44Ac 19:20 In this powerful way the word of the Lord kept spreading and growing stronger. 
44Ac 19:21 After these things had happened, Paul made up his mind to travel through Macedonia and Achaia and go on to Jerusalem. "After I go there," he said, "I must also see Rome." 
44Ac 19:22 So he sent Timothy and Erastus, two of his helpers, to Macedonia, while he spent more time in the province of Asia. 
44Ac 19:23 It was at this time that there was serious trouble in Ephesus because of the Way of the Lord. 
44Ac 19:24 A certain silversmith named Demetrius made silver models of the temple of the goddess Artemis, and his business brought a great deal of profit to the workers. 
44Ac 19:25 So he called them all together with others whose work was like theirs and said to them, "Men, you know that our prosperity comes from this work. 
44Ac 19:26 Now, you can see and hear for yourselves what this fellow Paul is doing. He says that hand-made gods are not gods at all, and he has succeeded in convincing many people, both here in Ephesus and in nearly the whole province of Asia. 
44Ac 19:27 There is the danger, then, that this business of ours will get a bad name. Not only that, but there is also the danger that the temple of the great goddess Artemis will come to mean nothing and that her greatness will be destroyed - the goddess worshiped by everyone in Asia and in all the world!" 
44Ac 19:28 As the crowd heard these words, they became furious and started shouting, "Great is Artemis of Ephesus!" 
44Ac 19:29 The uproar spread throughout the whole city. The mob grabbed Gaius and Aristarchus, two Macedonians who were traveling with Paul, and rushed with them to the theater. 
44Ac 19:30 Paul himself wanted to go before the crowd, but the believers would not let him. 
44Ac 19:31 Some of the provincial authorities, who were his friends, also sent him a message begging him not to show himself in the theater. 
44Ac 19:32 Meanwhile the whole meeting was in an uproar£º some people were shouting one thing, others were shouting something else, because most of them did not even know why they had come together. 
44Ac 19:33 Some of the people concluded that Alexander was responsible, since the Jews made him go up to the front. Then Alexander motioned with his hand for the people to be silent, and he tried to make a speech of defense. 
44Ac 19:34 But when they recognized that he was a Jew, they all shouted together the same thing for two hours£º "Great is Artemis of Ephesus!" 
44Ac 19:35 At last the city clerk was able to calm the crowd. "Fellow Ephesians!" he said. "Everyone knows that the city of Ephesus is the keeper of the temple of the great Artemis and of the sacred stone that fell down from heaven. 
44Ac 19:36 Nobody can deny these things. So then, you must calm down and not do anything reckless. 
44Ac 19:37 You have brought these men here even though they have not robbed temples or said evil things about our goddess. 
44Ac 19:38 If Demetrius and his workers have an accusation against anyone, we have the authorities and the regular days for court; charges can be made there. 
44Ac 19:39 But if there is something more that you want, it will have to be settled in a legal meeting of citizens. 
44Ac 19:40 For after what has happened today, there is the danger that we will be accused of a riot. There is no excuse for all this uproar, and we would not be able to give a good reason for it." 
44Ac 19:41 After saying this, he dismissed the meeting. 
44Ac 20:1 After the uproar died down, Paul called together the believers and with words of encouragement said good-bye to them. Then he left and went on to Macedonia. 
44Ac 20:2 He went through those regions and encouraged the people with many messages. Then he came to Achaia, 
44Ac 20:3 where he stayed three months. He was getting ready to go to Syria when he discovered that there were Jews plotting against him; so he decided to go back through Macedonia. 
44Ac 20:4 Sopater son of Pyrrhus, from Berea, went with him; so did Aristarchus and Secundus, from Thessalonica; Gaius, from Derbe; Tychicus and Trophimus, from the province of Asia; and Timothy. 
44Ac 20:5 They went ahead and waited for us in Troas. 
44Ac 20:6 We sailed from Philippi after the Festival of Unleavened Bread, and five days later we joined them in Troas, where we spent a week. 
44Ac 20:7 On Saturday evening we gathered together for the fellowship meal. Paul spoke to the people and kept on speaking until midnight, since he was going to leave the next day. 
44Ac 20:8 Many lamps were burning in the upstairs room where we were meeting. 
44Ac 20:9 A young man named Eutychus was sitting in the window, and as Paul kept on talking, Eutychus got sleepier and sleepier, until he finally went sound asleep and fell from the third story to the ground. When they picked him up, he was dead. 
44Ac 20:10 But Paul went down and threw himself on him and hugged him. "Don't worry," he said, "he is still alive!" 
44Ac 20:11 Then he went back upstairs, broke bread, and ate. After talking with them for a long time, even until sunrise, Paul left. 
44Ac 20:12 They took the young man home alive and were greatly comforted. 
44Ac 20:13 We went on ahead to the ship and sailed off to Assos, where we were going to take Paul aboard. He had told us to do this, because he was going there by land. 
44Ac 20:14 When he met us in Assos, we took him aboard and went on to Mitylene. 
44Ac 20:15 We sailed from there and arrived off Chios the next day. A day later we came to Samos, and the following day we reached Miletus. 
44Ac 20:16 Paul had decided to sail on by Ephesus, so as not to lose any time in the province of Asia. He was in a hurry to arrive in Jerusalem by the day of Pentecost, if at all possible. 
44Ac 20:17 From Miletus Paul sent a message to Ephesus, asking the elders of the church to meet him. 
44Ac 20:18 When they arrived, he said to them, "You know how I spent the whole time I was with you, from the first day I arrived in the province of Asia. 
44Ac 20:19 With all humility and many tears I did my work as the Lord's servant during the hard times that came to me because of the plots of some Jews. 
44Ac 20:20 You know that I did not hold back anything that would be of help to you as I preached and taught in public and in your homes. 
44Ac 20:21 To Jews and Gentiles alike I gave solemn warning that they should turn from their sins to God and believe in our Lord Jesus. 
44Ac 20:22 And now, in obedience to the Holy Spirit I am going to Jerusalem, not knowing what will happen to me there. 
44Ac 20:23 I only know that in every city the Holy Spirit has warned me that prison and troubles wait for me. 
44Ac 20:24 But I reckon my own life to be worth nothing to me; I only want to complete my mission and finish the work that the Lord Jesus gave me to do, which is to declare the Good News about the grace of God. 
44Ac 20:25 "I have gone about among all of you, preaching the Kingdom of God. And now I know that none of you will ever see me again. 
44Ac 20:26 So I solemnly declare to you this very day£º if any of you should be lost, I am not responsible. 
44Ac 20:27 For I have not held back from announcing to you the whole purpose of God. 
44Ac 20:28 So keep watch over yourselves and over all the flock which the Holy Spirit has placed in your care. Be shepherds of the church of God, which he made his own through the blood of his Son. 
44Ac 20:29 I know that after I leave, fierce wolves will come among you, and they will not spare the flock. 
44Ac 20:30 The time will come when some men from your own group will tell lies to lead the believers away after them. 
44Ac 20:31 Watch, then, and remember that with many tears, day and night, I taught every one of you for three years. 
44Ac 20:32 "And now I commend you to the care of God and to the message of his grace, which is able to build you up and give you the blessings God has for all his people. 
44Ac 20:33 I have not wanted anyone's silver or gold or clothing. 
44Ac 20:34 You yourselves know that I have worked with these hands of mine to provide everything that my companions and I have needed. 
44Ac 20:35 I have shown you in all things that by working hard in this way we must help the weak, remembering the words that the Lord Jesus himself said, 'There is more happiness in giving than in receiving.' " 
44Ac 20:36 When Paul finished, he knelt down with them and prayed. 
44Ac 20:37 They were all crying as they hugged him and kissed him good-bye. 
44Ac 20:38 They were especially sad because he had said that they would never see him again. And so they went with him to the ship. 
44Ac 21:1 We said good-bye to them and left. After sailing straight across, we came to Cos; the next day we reached Rhodes, and from there we went on to Patara. 
44Ac 21:2 There we found a ship that was going to Phoenicia, so we went aboard and sailed away. 
44Ac 21:3 We came to where we could see Cyprus, and then sailed south of it on to Syria. We went ashore at Tyre, where the ship was going to unload its cargo. 
44Ac 21:4 There we found some believers and stayed with them a week. By the power of the Spirit they told Paul not to go to Jerusalem. 
44Ac 21:5 But when our time with them was over, we left and went on our way. All of them, together with their wives and children, went with us out of the city to the beach, where we all knelt and prayed. 
44Ac 21:6 Then we said good-bye to one another, and we went on board the ship while they went back home. 
44Ac 21:7 We continued our voyage, sailing from Tyre to Ptolemais, where we greeted the believers and stayed with them for a day. 
44Ac 21:8 On the following day we left and arrived in Caesarea. There we stayed at the house of Philip the evangelist, one of the seven men who had been chosen as helpers in Jerusalem. 
44Ac 21:9 He had four unmarried daughters who proclaimed God's message. 
44Ac 21:10 We had been there for several days when a prophet named Agabus arrived from Judea. 
44Ac 21:11 He came to us, took Paul's belt, tied up his own feet and hands with it, and said, "This is what the Holy Spirit says£º The owner of this belt will be tied up in this way by the Jews in Jerusalem, and they will hand him over to the Gentiles." 
44Ac 21:12 When we heard this, we and the others there begged Paul not to go to Jerusalem. 
44Ac 21:13 But he answered, "What are you doing, crying like this and breaking my heart? I am ready not only to be tied up in Jerusalem but even to die there for the sake of the Lord Jesus." 
44Ac 21:14 We could not convince him, so we gave up and said, "May the Lord's will be done." 
44Ac 21:15 After spending some time there, we got our things ready and left for Jerusalem. 
44Ac 21:16 Some of the disciples from Caesarea also went with us and took us to the house of the man we were going to stay with - Mnason, from Cyprus, who had been a believer since the early days. 
44Ac 21:17 When we arrived in Jerusalem, the believers welcomed us warmly. 
44Ac 21:18 The next day Paul went with us to see James; and all the church elders were present. 
44Ac 21:19 Paul greeted them and gave a complete report of everything that God had done among the Gentiles through his work. 
44Ac 21:20 After hearing him, they all praised God. Then they said, "Brother Paul, you can see how many thousands of Jews have become believers, and how devoted they all are to the Law. 
44Ac 21:21 They have been told that you have been teaching all the Jews who live in Gentile countries to abandon the Law of Moses, telling them not to circumcise their children or follow the Jewish customs. 
44Ac 21:22 They are sure to hear that you have arrived. What should be done, then? 
44Ac 21:23 This is what we want you to do. There are four men here who have taken a vow. 
44Ac 21:24 Go along with them and join them in the ceremony of purification and pay their expenses; then they will be able to shave their heads. In this way everyone will know that there is no truth in any of the things that they have been told about you, but that you yourself live in accordance with the Law of Moses. 
44Ac 21:25 But as for the Gentiles who have become believers, we have sent them a letter telling them we decided that they must not eat any food that has been offered to idols, or any blood, or any animal that has been strangled, and that they must keep themselves from sexual immorality." 
44Ac 21:26 So Paul took the men and the next day performed the ceremony of purification with them. Then he went into the Temple and gave notice of how many days it would be until the end of the period of purification, when a sacrifice would be offered for each one of them. 
44Ac 21:27 But just when the seven days were about to come to an end, some Jews from the province of Asia saw Paul in the Temple. They stirred up the whole crowd and grabbed Paul. 
44Ac 21:28 "People of Israel!" they shouted. "Help! This is the man who goes everywhere teaching everyone against the people of Israel, the Law of Moses, and this Temple. And now he has even brought some Gentiles into the Temple and defiled this holy place!" 
44Ac 21:29 (They said this because they had seen Trophimus from Ephesus with Paul in the city, and they thought that Paul had taken him into the Temple.) 
44Ac 21:30 Confusion spread through the whole city, and the people all ran together, grabbed Paul, and dragged him out of the Temple. At once the Temple doors were closed. 
44Ac 21:31 The mob was trying to kill Paul, when a report was sent up to the commander of the Roman troops that all of Jerusalem was rioting. 
44Ac 21:32 At once the commander took some officers and soldiers and rushed down to the crowd. When the people saw him with the soldiers, they stopped beating Paul. 
44Ac 21:33 The commander went over to Paul, arrested him, and ordered him to be bound with two chains. Then he asked, "Who is this man, and what has he done?" 
44Ac 21:34 Some in the crowd shouted one thing, others something else. There was such confusion that the commander could not find out exactly what had happened, so he ordered his men to take Paul up into the fort. 
44Ac 21:35 They got as far as the steps with him, and then the soldiers had to carry him because the mob was so wild. 
44Ac 21:36 They were all coming after him and screaming, "Kill him!" 
44Ac 21:37 As the soldiers were about to take Paul into the fort, he spoke to the commander£º "May I say something to you?" "You speak Greek, do you?" the commander asked. 
44Ac 21:38 "Then you are not that Egyptian fellow who some time ago started a revolution and led four thousand armed terrorists out into the desert?" 
44Ac 21:39 Paul answered, "I am a Jew, born in Tarsus in Cilicia, a citizen of an important city. Please let me speak to the people." 
44Ac 21:40 The commander gave him permission, so Paul stood on the steps and motioned with his hand for the people to be silent. When they were quiet, Paul spoke to them in Hebrew£º 
44Ac 22:1 "My fellow Jews, listen to me as I make my defense before you!" 
44Ac 22:2 When they heard him speaking to them in Hebrew, they became even quieter; and Paul went on£º 
44Ac 22:3 "I am a Jew, born in Tarsus in Cilicia, but brought up here in Jerusalem as a student of Gamaliel. I received strict instruction in the Law of our ancestors and was just as dedicated to God as are all of you who are here today. 
44Ac 22:4 I persecuted to the death the people who followed this Way. I arrested men and women and threw them into prison. 
44Ac 22:5 The High Priest and the whole Council can prove that I am telling the truth. I received from them letters written to fellow Jews in Damascus, so I went there to arrest these people and bring them back in chains to Jerusalem to be punished. 
44Ac 22:6 "As I was traveling and coming near Damascus, about midday a bright light from the sky flashed suddenly around me. 
44Ac 22:7 I fell to the ground and heard a voice saying to me, 'Saul, Saul! Why do you persecute me?' 
44Ac 22:8 'Who are you, Lord?' I asked. 'I am Jesus of Nazareth, whom you persecute,' he said to me. 
44Ac 22:9 The men with me saw the light, but did not hear the voice of the one who was speaking to me. 
44Ac 22:10 I asked, 'What shall I do, Lord?' and the Lord said to me, 'Get up and go into Damascus, and there you will be told everything that God has determined for you to do.' 
44Ac 22:11 I was blind because of the bright light, and so my companions took me by the hand and led me into Damascus. 
44Ac 22:12 "In that city was a man named Ananias, a religious man who obeyed our Law and was highly respected by all the Jews living there. 
44Ac 22:13 He came to me, stood by me, and said, 'Brother Saul, see again!' At that very moment I saw again and looked at him. 
44Ac 22:14 He said, 'The God of our ancestors has chosen you to know his will, to see his righteous Servant, and to hear him speaking with his own voice. 
44Ac 22:15 For you will be a witness for him to tell everyone what you have seen and heard. 
44Ac 22:16 And now, why wait any longer? Get up and be baptized and have your sins washed away by praying to him.' 
44Ac 22:17 "I went back to Jerusalem, and while I was praying in the Temple, I had a vision, 
44Ac 22:18 in which I saw the Lord, as he said to me, 'Hurry and leave Jerusalem quickly, because the people here will not accept your witness about me.' 
44Ac 22:19 'Lord,' I answered, 'they know very well that I went to the synagogues and arrested and beat those who believe in you. 
44Ac 22:20 And when your witness Stephen was put to death, I myself was there, approving of his murder and taking care of the cloaks of his murderers.' 
44Ac 22:21 'Go,' the Lord said to me, 'for I will send you far away to the Gentiles.' " 
44Ac 22:22 The people listened to Paul until he said this; but then they started shouting at the top of their voices, "Away with him! Kill him! He's not fit to live!" 
44Ac 22:23 They were screaming, waving their clothes, and throwing dust up in the air. 
44Ac 22:24 The Roman commander ordered his men to take Paul into the fort, and he told them to whip him in order to find out why the Jews were screaming like this against him. 
44Ac 22:25 But when they had tied him up to be whipped, Paul said to the officer standing there, "Is it lawful for you to whip a Roman citizen who hasn't even been tried for any crime?" 
44Ac 22:26 When the officer heard this, he went to the commander and asked him, "What are you doing? That man is a Roman citizen!" 
44Ac 22:27 So the commander went to Paul and asked him, "Tell me, are you a Roman citizen?" "Yes," answered Paul. 
44Ac 22:28 The commander said, "I became one by paying a large amount of money." "But I am one by birth," Paul answered. 
44Ac 22:29 At once the men who were going to question Paul drew back from him; and the commander was frightened when he realized that Paul was a Roman citizen and that he had put him in chains. 
44Ac 22:30 The commander wanted to find out for sure what the Jews were accusing Paul of; so the next day he had Paul's chains taken off and ordered the chief priests and the whole Council to meet. Then he took Paul and made him stand before them. 
44Ac 23:1 Paul looked straight at the Council and said, "My fellow Israelites! My conscience is perfectly clear about the way in which I have lived before God to this very day." 
44Ac 23:2 The High Priest Ananias ordered those who were standing close to Paul to strike him on the mouth. 
44Ac 23:3 Paul said to him, "God will certainly strike you - you whitewashed wall! You sit there to judge me according to the Law, yet you break the Law by ordering them to strike me!" 
44Ac 23:4 The men close to Paul said to him, "You are insulting God's High Priest!" 
44Ac 23:5 Paul answered, "My fellow Israelites, I did not know that he was the High Priest. The scripture says, 'You must not speak evil of the ruler of your people.' " 
44Ac 23:6 When Paul saw that some of the group were Sadducees and the others were Pharisees, he called out in the Council, "Fellow Israelites! I am a Pharisee, the son of Pharisees. I am on trial here because of the hope I have that the dead will rise to life!" 
44Ac 23:7 As soon as he said this, the Pharisees and Sadducees started to quarrel, and the group was divided. 
44Ac 23:8 (For the Sadducees say that people will not rise from death and that there are no angels or spirits; but the Pharisees believe in all three.) 
44Ac 23:9 The shouting became louder, and some of the teachers of the Law who belonged to the party of the Pharisees stood up and protested strongly£º "We cannot find a thing wrong with this man! Perhaps a spirit or an angel really did speak to him!" 
44Ac 23:10 The argument became so violent that the commander was afraid that Paul would be torn to pieces. So he ordered his soldiers to go down into the group, get Paul away from them, and take him into the fort. 
44Ac 23:11 That night the Lord stood by Paul and said, "Don't be afraid! You have given your witness for me here in Jerusalem, and you must also do the same in Rome." 
44Ac 23:12 The next morning some Jews met together and made a plan. They took a vow that they would not eat or drink anything until they had killed Paul. 
44Ac 23:13 There were more than forty who planned this together. 
44Ac 23:14 Then they went to the chief priests and elders and said, "We have taken a solemn vow together not to eat a thing until we have killed Paul. 
44Ac 23:15 Now then, you and the Council send word to the Roman commander to bring Paul down to you, pretending that you want to get more accurate information about him. But we will be ready to kill him before he ever gets here." 
44Ac 23:16 But the son of Paul's sister heard about the plot; so he went to the fort and told Paul. 
44Ac 23:17 Then Paul called one of the officers and said to him, "Take this young man to the commander; he has something to tell him." 
44Ac 23:18 The officer took him, led him to the commander, and said, "The prisoner Paul called me and asked me to bring this young man to you, because he has something to say to you." 
44Ac 23:19 The commander took him by the hand, led him off by himself, and asked him, "What do you have to tell me?" 
44Ac 23:20 He said, "The Jewish authorities have agreed to ask you tomorrow to take Paul down to the Council, pretending that the Council wants to get more accurate information about him. 
44Ac 23:21 But don't listen to them, because there are more than forty men who will be hiding and waiting for him. They have taken a vow not to eat or drink until they have killed him. They are now ready to do it and are waiting for your decision." 
44Ac 23:22 The commander said, "Don't tell anyone that you have reported this to me." And he sent the young man away. 
44Ac 23:23 Then the commander called two of his officers and said, "Get two hundred soldiers ready to go to Caesarea, together with seventy horsemen and two hundred spearmen, and be ready to leave by nine o'clock tonight. 
44Ac 23:24 Provide some horses for Paul to ride and get him safely through to Governor Felix." 
44Ac 23:25 Then the commander wrote a letter that went like this£º 
44Ac 23:26 "Claudius Lysias to His Excellency, Governor Felix£º Greetings. 
44Ac 23:27 The Jews seized this man and were about to kill him. I learned that he is a Roman citizen, so I went with my soldiers and rescued him. 
44Ac 23:28 I wanted to know what they were accusing him of, so I took him down to their Council. 
44Ac 23:29 I found out that he had not done a thing for which he deserved to die or be put in prison; the accusation against him had to do with questions about their own law. 
44Ac 23:30 And when I was informed that there was a plot against him, at once I decided to send him to you. I have told his accusers to make their charges against him before you." 
44Ac 23:31 The soldiers carried out their orders. They got Paul and took him that night as far as Antipatris. 
44Ac 23:32 The next day the foot soldiers returned to the fort and left the horsemen to go on with him. 
44Ac 23:33 They took him to Caesarea, delivered the letter to the governor, and turned Paul over to him. 
44Ac 23:34 The governor read the letter and asked Paul what province he was from. When he found out that he was from Cilicia, 
44Ac 23:35 he said, "I will hear you when your accusers arrive." Then he gave orders for Paul to be kept under guard in the governor's headquarters. 
44Ac 24:1 Five days later the High Priest Ananias went to Caesarea with some elders and a lawyer named Tertullus. They appeared before Governor Felix and made their charges against Paul. 
44Ac 24:2 Then Paul was called in, and Tertullus began to make his accusation, as follows£º "Your Excellency! Your wise leadership has brought us a long period of peace, and many necessary reforms are being made for the good of our country. 
44Ac 24:3 We welcome this everywhere and at all times, and we are deeply grateful to you. 
44Ac 24:4 I do not want to take up too much of your time, however, so I beg you to be kind and listen to our brief account. 
44Ac 24:5 We found this man to be a dangerous nuisance; he starts riots among Jews all over the world and is a leader of the party of the Nazarenes. 
44Ac 24:6 He also tried to defile the Temple, and we arrested him. 
44Ac 24:7 OMITTED TEXT
44Ac 24:8 If you question this man, you yourself will be able to learn from him all the things that we are accusing him of." 
44Ac 24:9 The Jews joined in the accusation and said that all this was true. 
44Ac 24:10 The governor then motioned to Paul to speak, and Paul said, "I know that you have been a judge over this nation for many years, and so I am happy to defend myself before you. 
44Ac 24:11 As you can find out for yourself, it was no more than twelve days ago that I went to Jerusalem to worship. 
44Ac 24:12 The Jews did not find me arguing with anyone in the Temple, nor did they find me stirring up the people, either in the synagogues or anywhere else in the city. 
44Ac 24:13 Nor can they give you proof of the accusations they now bring against me. 
44Ac 24:14 I do admit this to you£º I worship the God of our ancestors by following that Way which they say is false. But I also believe in everything written in the Law of Moses and the books of the prophets. 
44Ac 24:15 I have the same hope in God that these themselves have, namely, that all people, both the good and the bad, will rise from death. 
44Ac 24:16 And so I do my best always to have a clear conscience before God and people. 
44Ac 24:17 "After being away from Jerusalem for several years, I went there to take some money to my own people and to offer sacrifices. 
44Ac 24:18 It was while I was doing this that they found me in the Temple after I had completed the ceremony of purification. There was no crowd with me and no disorder. 
44Ac 24:19 But some Jews from the province of Asia were there; they themselves ought to come before you and make their accusations if they have anything against me. 
44Ac 24:20 Or let these who are here tell what crime they found me guilty of when I stood before the Council - 
44Ac 24:21 except for the one thing I called out when I stood before them£º 'I am being tried by you today for believing that the dead will rise to life.' " 
44Ac 24:22 Then Felix, who was well informed about the Way, brought the hearing to a close. "When the commander Lysias arrives," he told them, "I will decide your case." 
44Ac 24:23 He ordered the officer in charge of Paul to keep him under guard, but to give him some freedom and allow his friends to provide for his needs. 
44Ac 24:24 After some days Felix came with his wife Drusilla, who was Jewish. He sent for Paul and listened to him as he talked about faith in Christ Jesus. 
44Ac 24:25 But as Paul went on discussing about goodness, self-control, and the coming Day of Judgment, Felix was afraid and said, "You may leave now. I will call you again when I get the chance." 
44Ac 24:26 At the same time he was hoping that Paul would give him some money; and for this reason he would call for him often and talk with him. 
44Ac 24:27 After two years had passed, Porcius Festus succeeded Felix as governor. Felix wanted to gain favor with the Jews so he left Paul in prison. 
44Ac 25:1 Three days after Festus arrived in the province, he went from Caesarea to Jerusalem, 
44Ac 25:2 where the chief priests and the Jewish leaders brought their charges against Paul. They begged Festus 
44Ac 25:3 to do them the favor of having Paul come to Jerusalem, for they had made a plot to kill him on the way. 
44Ac 25:4 Festus answered, "Paul is being kept a prisoner in Caesarea, and I myself will be going back there soon. 
44Ac 25:5 Let your leaders go to Caesarea with me and accuse the man if he has done anything wrong." 
44Ac 25:6 Festus spent another eight or ten days with them and then went to Caesarea. On the next day he sat down in the judgment court and ordered Paul to be brought in. 
44Ac 25:7 When Paul arrived, the Jews who had come from Jerusalem stood around him and started making many serious charges against him, which they were not able to prove. 
44Ac 25:8 But Paul defended himself£º "I have done nothing wrong against the Law of the Jews or against the Temple or against the Roman Emperor." 
44Ac 25:9 But Festus wanted to gain favor with the Jews, so he asked Paul, "Would you be willing to go to Jerusalem and be tried on these charges before me there?" 
44Ac 25:10 Paul said, "I am standing before the Emperor's own judgment court, where I should be tried. I have done no wrong to the Jews, as you yourself well know. 
44Ac 25:11 If I have broken the law and done something for which I deserve the death penalty, I do not ask to escape it. But if there is no truth in the charges they bring against me, no one can hand me over to them. I appeal to the Emperor." 
44Ac 25:12 Then Festus, after conferring with his advisers, answered, "You have appealed to the Emperor, so to the Emperor you will go." 
44Ac 25:13 Some time later King Agrippa and Bernice came to Caesarea to pay a visit of welcome to Festus. 
44Ac 25:14 After they had been there several days, Festus explained Paul's situation to the king£º "There is a man here who was left a prisoner by Felix; 
44Ac 25:15 and when I went to Jerusalem, the Jewish chief priests and elders brought charges against him and asked me to condemn him. 
44Ac 25:16 But I told them that we Romans are not in the habit of handing over any who are accused of a crime before they have met their accusers face-to-face and have had the chance of defending themselves against the accusation. 
44Ac 25:17 When they came here, then, I lost no time, but on the very next day I sat in the judgment court and ordered the man to be brought in. 
44Ac 25:18 His opponents stood up, but they did not accuse him of any of the evil crimes that I thought they would. 
44Ac 25:19 All they had were some arguments with him about their own religion and about a man named Jesus, who has died; but Paul claims that he is alive. 
44Ac 25:20 I was undecided about how I could get information on these matters, so I asked Paul if he would be willing to go to Jerusalem and be tried there on these charges. 
44Ac 25:21 But Paul appealed; he asked to be kept under guard and to let the Emperor decide his case. So I gave orders for him to be kept under guard until I could send him to the Emperor." 
44Ac 25:22 Agrippa said to Festus, "I would like to hear this man myself." "You will hear him tomorrow," Festus answered. 
44Ac 25:23 The next day Agrippa and Bernice came with great pomp and ceremony and entered the audience hall with the military chiefs and the leading men of the city. Festus gave the order, and Paul was brought in. 
44Ac 25:24 Festus said, "King Agrippa and all who are here with us£º You see this man against whom all the Jewish people, both here and in Jerusalem, have brought complaints to me. They scream that he should not live any longer. 
44Ac 25:25 But I could not find that he had done anything for which he deserved the death sentence. And since he himself made an appeal to the Emperor, I have decided to send him. 
44Ac 25:26 But I have nothing definite about him to write to the Emperor. So I have brought him here before you - and especially before you, King Agrippa! - so that, after investigating his case, I may have something to write. 
44Ac 25:27 For it seems unreasonable to me to send a prisoner without clearly indicating the charges against him." 
44Ac 26:1 Agrippa said to Paul, "You have permission to speak on your own behalf." Paul stretched out his hand and defended himself as follows£º 
44Ac 26:2 "King Agrippa! I consider myself fortunate that today I am to defend myself before you from all the things these Jews accuse me of, 
44Ac 26:3 particularly since you know so well all the Jewish customs and disputes. I ask you, then, to listen to me with patience. 
44Ac 26:4 "All the Jews know how I have lived ever since I was young. They know how I have spent my whole life, at first in my own country and then in Jerusalem. 
44Ac 26:5 They have always known, if they are willing to testify, that from the very first I have lived as a member of the strictest party of our religion, the Pharisees. 
44Ac 26:6 And now I stand here to be tried because of the hope I have in the promise that God made to our ancestors - 
44Ac 26:7 the very thing that the twelve tribes of our people hope to receive, as they worship God day and night. And it is because of this hope, Your Majesty, that I am being accused by these Jews! 
44Ac 26:8 Why do you who are here find it impossible to believe that God raises the dead? 
44Ac 26:9 "I myself thought that I should do everything I could against the cause of Jesus of Nazareth. 
44Ac 26:10 That is what I did in Jerusalem. I received authority from the chief priests and put many of God's people in prison; and when they were sentenced to death, I also voted against them. 
44Ac 26:11 Many times I had them punished in the synagogues and tried to make them deny their faith. I was so furious with them that I even went to foreign cities to persecute them. 
44Ac 26:12 "It was for this purpose that I went to Damascus with authority and orders from the chief priests. 
44Ac 26:13 It was on the road at midday, Your Majesty, that I saw a light much brighter than the sun, coming from the sky and shining around me and the men traveling with me. 
44Ac 26:14 All of us fell to the ground, and I heard a voice say to me in Hebrew, 'Saul, Saul! Why are you persecuting me? You are hurting yourself by hitting back, like an ox kicking against its owner's stick.' 
44Ac 26:15 'Who are you, Lord?' I asked. And the Lord answered, 'I am Jesus, whom you persecute. 
44Ac 26:16 But get up and stand on your feet. I have appeared to you to appoint you as my servant. You are to tell others what you have seen of me today and what I will show you in the future. 
44Ac 26:17 I will rescue you from the people of Israel and from the Gentiles to whom I will send you. 
44Ac 26:18 You are to open their eyes and turn them from the darkness to the light and from the power of Satan to God, so that through their faith in me they will have their sins forgiven and receive their place among God's chosen people.' 
44Ac 26:19 "And so, King Agrippa, I did not disobey the vision I had from heaven. 
44Ac 26:20 First in Damascus and in Jerusalem and then in the whole country of Israel and among the Gentiles, I preached that they must repent of their sins and turn to God and do the things that would show they had repented. 
44Ac 26:21 It was for this reason that these Jews seized me while I was in the Temple, and they tried to kill me. 
44Ac 26:22 But to this very day I have been helped by God, and so I stand here giving my witness to all, to small and great alike. What I say is the very same thing which the prophets and Moses said was going to happen£º 
44Ac 26:23 that the Messiah must suffer and be the first one to rise from death, to announce the light of salvation to the Jews and to the Gentiles." 
44Ac 26:24 As Paul defended himself in this way, Festus shouted at him, "You are mad, Paul! Your great learning is driving you mad!" 
44Ac 26:25 Paul answered, "I am not mad, Your Excellency! I am speaking the sober truth. 
44Ac 26:26 King Agrippa! I can speak to you with all boldness, because you know about these things. I am sure that you have taken notice of every one of them, for this thing has not happened hidden away in a corner. 
44Ac 26:27 King Agrippa, do you believe the prophets? I know that you do!" 
44Ac 26:28 Agrippa said to Paul, "In this short time do you think you will make me a Christian?" 
44Ac 26:29 "Whether a short time or a long time," Paul answered, "my prayer to God is that you and all the rest of you who are listening to me today might become what I am - except, of course, for these chains!" 
44Ac 26:30 Then the king, the governor, Bernice, and all the others got up, 
44Ac 26:31 and after leaving they said to each other, "This man has not done anything for which he should die or be put in prison." 
44Ac 26:32 And Agrippa said to Festus, "This man could have been released if he had not appealed to the Emperor." 
44Ac 27:1 When it was decided that we should sail to Italy, they handed Paul and some other prisoners over to Julius, an officer in the Roman army regiment called "The Emperor's Regiment." 
44Ac 27:2 We went aboard a ship from Adramyttium, which was ready to leave for the seaports of the province of Asia, and we sailed away. Aristarchus, a Macedonian from Thessalonica, was with us. 
44Ac 27:3 The next day we arrived at Sidon. Julius was kind to Paul and allowed him to go and see his friends, to be given what he needed. 
44Ac 27:4 We went on from there, and because the winds were blowing against us, we sailed on the sheltered side of the island of Cyprus. 
44Ac 27:5 We crossed over the sea off Cilicia and Pamphylia and came to Myra in Lycia. 
44Ac 27:6 There the officer found a ship from Alexandria that was going to sail for Italy, so he put us aboard. 
44Ac 27:7 We sailed slowly for several days and with great difficulty finally arrived off the town of Cnidus. The wind would not let us go any farther in that direction, so we sailed down the sheltered side of the island of Crete, passing by Cape Salmone. 
44Ac 27:8 We kept close to the coast and with great difficulty came to a place called Safe Harbors, not far from the town of Lasea. 
44Ac 27:9 We spent a long time there, until it became dangerous to continue the voyage, for by now the Day of Atonement was already past. So Paul gave them this advice£º 
44Ac 27:10 "Men, I see that our voyage from here on will be dangerous; there will be great damage to the cargo and to the ship, and loss of life as well." 
44Ac 27:11 But the army officer was convinced by what the captain and the owner of the ship said, and not by what Paul said. 
44Ac 27:12 The harbor was not a good one to spend the winter in; so almost everyone was in favor of putting out to sea and trying to reach Phoenix, if possible, in order to spend the winter there. Phoenix is a harbor in Crete that faces southwest and northwest. 
44Ac 27:13 A soft wind from the south began to blow, and the men thought that they could carry out their plan, so they pulled up the anchor and sailed as close as possible along the coast of Crete. 
44Ac 27:14 But soon a very strong wind - the one called "Northeaster" - blew down from the island. 
44Ac 27:15 It hit the ship, and since it was impossible to keep the ship headed into the wind, we gave up trying and let it be carried along by the wind. 
44Ac 27:16 We got some shelter when we passed to the south of the little island of Cauda. There, with some difficulty we managed to make the ship's boat secure. 
44Ac 27:17 They pulled it aboard and then fastened some ropes tight around the ship. They were afraid that they might run into the sandbanks off the coast of Libya, so they lowered the sail and let the ship be carried by the wind. 
44Ac 27:18 The violent storm continued, so on the next day they began to throw some of the ship's cargo overboard, 
44Ac 27:19 and on the following day they threw part of the ship's equipment overboard. 
44Ac 27:20 For many days we could not see the sun or the stars, and the wind kept on blowing very hard. We finally gave up all hope of being saved. 
44Ac 27:21 After everyone had gone a long time without food, Paul stood before them and said, "You should have listened to me and not have sailed from Crete; then we would have avoided all this damage and loss. 
44Ac 27:22 But now I beg you, take courage! Not one of you will lose your life; only the ship will be lost. 
44Ac 27:23 For last night an angel of the God to whom I belong and whom I worship came to me 
44Ac 27:24 and said, 'Don't be afraid, Paul! You must stand before the Emperor. And God in his goodness to you has spared the lives of all those who are sailing with you.' 
44Ac 27:25 So take courage, men! For I trust in God that it will be just as I was told. 
44Ac 27:26 But we will be driven ashore on some island." 
44Ac 27:27 It was the fourteenth night, and we were being driven in the Mediterranean by the storm. About midnight the sailors suspected that we were getting close to land. 
44Ac 27:28 So they dropped a line with a weight tied to it and found that the water was one hundred and twenty feet deep; a little later they did the same and found that it was ninety feet deep. 
44Ac 27:29 They were afraid that the ship would go on the rocks, so they lowered four anchors from the back of the ship and prayed for daylight. 
44Ac 27:30 Then the sailors tried to escape from the ship; they lowered the boat into the water and pretended that they were going to put out some anchors from the front of the ship. 
44Ac 27:31 But Paul said to the army officer and soldiers, "If the sailors don't stay on board, you have no hope of being saved." 
44Ac 27:32 So the soldiers cut the ropes that held the boat and let it go. 
44Ac 27:33 Just before dawn, Paul begged them all to eat some food£º "You have been waiting for fourteen days now, and all this time you have not eaten a thing. 
44Ac 27:34 I beg you, then, eat some food; you need it in order to survive. Not even a hair of your heads will be lost." 
44Ac 27:35 After saying this, Paul took some bread, gave thanks to God before them all, broke it, and began to eat. 
44Ac 27:36 They took courage, and every one of them also ate some food. 
44Ac 27:37 There was a total of 276 of us on board. 
44Ac 27:38 After everyone had eaten enough, they lightened the ship by throwing all the wheat into the sea. 
44Ac 27:39 When day came, the sailors did not recognize the coast, but they noticed a bay with a beach and decided that, if possible, they would run the ship aground there. 
44Ac 27:40 So they cut off the anchors and let them sink in the sea, and at the same time they untied the ropes that held the steering oars. Then they raised the sail at the front of the ship so that the wind would blow the ship forward, and we headed for shore. 
44Ac 27:41 But the ship hit a sandbank and went aground; the front part of the ship got stuck and could not move, while the back part was being broken to pieces by the violence of the waves. 
44Ac 27:42 The soldiers made a plan to kill all the prisoners, in order to keep them from swimming ashore and escaping. 
44Ac 27:43 But the army officer wanted to save Paul, so he stopped them from doing this. Instead, he ordered everyone who could swim to jump overboard first and swim ashore; 
44Ac 27:44 the rest were to follow, holding on to the planks or to some broken pieces of the ship. And this was how we all got safely ashore. 
44Ac 28:1 When we were safely ashore, we learned that the island was called Malta. 
44Ac 28:2 The natives there were very friendly to us. It had started to rain and was cold, so they built a fire and made us all welcome. 
44Ac 28:3 Paul gathered up a bundle of sticks and was putting them on the fire when a snake came out on account of the heat and fastened itself to his hand. 
44Ac 28:4 The natives saw the snake hanging on Paul's hand and said to one another, "This man must be a murderer, but Fate will not let him live, even though he escaped from the sea." 
44Ac 28:5 But Paul shook the snake off into the fire without being harmed at all. 
44Ac 28:6 They were waiting for him to swell up or suddenly fall down dead. But after waiting for a long time and not seeing anything unusual happening to him, they changed their minds and said, "He is a god!" 
44Ac 28:7 Not far from that place were some fields that belonged to Publius, the chief of the island. He welcomed us kindly and for three days we were his guests. 
44Ac 28:8 Publius' father was in bed, sick with fever and dysentery. Paul went into his room, prayed, placed his hands on him, and healed him. 
44Ac 28:9 When this happened, all the other sick people on the island came and were healed. 
44Ac 28:10 They gave us many gifts, and when we sailed, they put on board what we needed for the voyage. 
44Ac 28:11 After three months we sailed away on a ship from Alexandria, called "The Twin Gods," which had spent the winter in the island. 
44Ac 28:12 We arrived in the city of Syracuse and stayed there for three days. 
44Ac 28:13 From there we sailed on and arrived in the city of Rhegium. The next day a wind began to blow from the south, and in two days we came to the town of Puteoli. 
44Ac 28:14 We found some believers there who asked us to stay with them a week. And so we came to Rome. 
44Ac 28:15 The believers in Rome heard about us and came as far as the towns of Market of Appius and Three Inns to meet us. When Paul saw them, he thanked God and was greatly encouraged. 
44Ac 28:16 When we arrived in Rome, Paul was allowed to live by himself with a soldier guarding him. 
44Ac 28:17 After three days Paul called the local Jewish leaders to a meeting. When they had gathered, he said to them, "My fellow Israelites, even though I did nothing against our people or the customs that we received from our ancestors, I was made a prisoner in Jerusalem and handed over to the Romans. 
44Ac 28:18 After questioning me, the Romans wanted to release me, because they found that I had done nothing for which I deserved to die. 
44Ac 28:19 But when the Jews opposed this, I was forced to appeal to the Emperor, even though I had no accusation to make against my own people. 
44Ac 28:20 That is why I asked to see you and talk with you. As a matter of fact, I am bound in chains like this for the sake of him for whom the people of Israel hope." 
44Ac 28:21 They said to him, "We have not received any letters from Judea about you, nor have any of our people come from there with any news or anything bad to say about you. 
44Ac 28:22 But we would like to hear your ideas, because we know that everywhere people speak against this party to which you belong." 
44Ac 28:23 So they set a date with Paul, and a large number of them came that day to the place where Paul was staying. From morning till night he explained to them his message about the Kingdom of God, and he tried to convince them about Jesus by quoting from the Law of Moses and the writings of the prophets. 
44Ac 28:24 Some of them were convinced by his words, but others would not believe. 
44Ac 28:25 So they left, disagreeing among themselves, after Paul had said this one thing£º "How well the Holy Spirit spoke through the prophet Isaiah to your ancestors! 
44Ac 28:26 For he said, 'Go and say to this people£º You will listen and listen, but not understand; you will look and look, but not see, 
44Ac 28:27 because this people's minds are dull, and they have stopped up their ears and closed their eyes. Otherwise, their eyes would see, their ears would hear, their minds would understand, and they would turn to me, says God, and I would heal them.' " 
44Ac 28:28 And Paul concluded£º "You are to know, then, that God's message of salvation has been sent to the Gentiles. They will listen!" 
